        {
          "id": "5500703c-56c9-4fa3-998f-29e1a3fa4ed3",
          "user": "Dr. AI Assistant",
          "content": "Hello! How can I assist you with the heart case today?",
          "type": "text",
          "timestamp": "2026-01-16T00:14:49.782801"
        },
        {
          "id": "237de150-f446-4217-99e9-b99ad6de832c",
          "user": "Dr. Anonymous",
          "content": "i want to know about the heart diseases",
          "type": "text",
          "timestamp": "2026-01-16T00:15:09.714670"
        },
        {
          "id": "60fd0705-8168-4b86-b89c-01be73b727b8",
          "user": "Dr. AI Assistant",
          "content": "Heart diseases encompass a range of conditions affecting the heart's structure and function. Key types include:\n\n1. **Coronary Artery Disease (CAD)**: Caused by the buildup of plaque in the coronary arteries, leading to reduced blood flow to the heart muscle, which can result in angina or heart attacks.\n\n2. **Heart Failure**: A condition where the heart cannot pump enough blood to meet the body's needs. It can be due to various causes, including CAD, hypertension, and cardiomyopathy.\n\n3. **Arrhythmias**: Abnormal heart rhythms that can lead to palpitations, dizziness, or even sudden cardiac arrest. Common types include atrial fibrillation and ventricular tachycardia.\n\n4. **Valvular Heart Disease**: Involves damage to or a defect in one of the heart's valves, which can lead to stenosis (narrowing) or regurgitation (leaking).\n\n5. **Cardiomyopathy**: A disease of the heart muscle that affects its size, shape, and ability to pump blood. Types include dilated, hypertrophic, and restrictive cardiomyopathy.\n\n6. **Congenital Heart Defects**: Structural problems with the heart present",
          "type": "text",
          "timestamp": "2026-01-16T00:15:16.786996"
        },
        {
          "id": "7861a1c8-00be-4f4b-a583-a8ef6de54af6",
